,"1556":"1556","1577":"1577","1598":"1598","1530":"1530","1585":"1585","1562":"1562","1608":"1608","1627":"1627","1549":"1549","St Mary Woolnoth with St Mary Woolchurch Haw, London, England":"St Mary Woolnoth with St Mary Woolchurch Haw, London, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Shelsley Beauchamp, Worcestershire, England":"Shelsley Beauchamp, Worcestershire, England","London, England":"London, England","St Briavels, Gloucestershire, England":"St Briavels, Gloucestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Stephens","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Stevens  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Stevens","meanings":["English (London), Flemish, Dutch, and North German: patronymic from the personal name   Steven  . The surname of Flemish origin is also found in the Walloon part of Belgium. In North America, the English form of the surname has also absorbed some like-sounding Jewish names and various other European cognates, e.g. Greek   Stefanidis  , Serbian <b>Stevanović</b> (see   Stevanovic  ), Slovenian and Slovak <b>Štefanič</b> (see   Stefanic  )."]}]},{"name":"Humffrey","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Humphrey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Humphrey","meanings":["From a Norman name, <i>Hunfrid</i>, of Germanic origin, derived from <i>hun</i> ‘bear-cub, warrior’ + <i>fred</i>, <i>frid</i> ‘peace’. The Norman form absorbed the native Old English form, <i>Hunfrith</i>, which existed in England before the Conquest. The spelling with <i>-ph-</i> reflects classicizing influence. Since the 16th century it has enjoyed a modest popularity in England, having been borne most notably by the youngest son of  King Henry IV , the Duke of Gloucester (  1391–1447 ), known as ‘Duke Humphrey’. He was noted as a patron of literature, and founded what became the Bodleian Library at Oxford. In modern times, probably the most famous bearer has been the film star  Humphrey Bogart  (  1899–1957 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":19,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705202,"age":28,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705205,"age":39,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705206,"age":41,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705207,"age":55,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705210,"age":70,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Humffrey Stephens was born in 1530, in England. He married Marie Jeffres on 30 September 1577, in Shelsley Beauchamp, Worcestershire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. He died in 1608, in his hometown, at the age of 78."},"et":{"1530–1608":"1530–1608","1535–Female":"1535–Surnud","1560–1598":"1560–1598","1562–Female":"1562–Surnud","1577–Male":"1577–Surnud","1556–1627":"1556–1627","28 May 1562":"28. mai 1562","1560":"1560","1571":"1571","30 September 1577":"30. september 1577","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1535":"1535","1600":"1600","1556":"1556","1577":"1577","1598":"1598","1530":"1530","1585":"1585","1562":"1562","1608":"1608","1627":"1627","1549":"1549","St Mary Woolnoth with St Mary Woolchurch Haw, London, England":"St Mary Woolnoth with St Mary Woolchurch Haw, London, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Shelsley Beauchamp, Worcestershire, England":"Shelsley Beauchamp, Worcestershire, England","London, England":"London, England","St Briavels, Gloucestershire, England":"St Briavels, Gloucestershire, England"},"fi":{"1530–1608":"1530–1608","1535–Female":"1535–Kuollut","1560–1598":"1560–1598","1562–Female":"1562–Kuollut","1577–Male":"1577–Kuollut","1556–1627":"1556–1627","28 May 1562":"28. toukokuuta 1562","1560":"1560","1571":"1571","30 September 1577":"30. syyskuuta 1577","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1535":"1535","1600":"1600","1556":"1556","1577":"1577","1598":"1598","1530":"1530","1585":"1585","1562":"1562","1608":"1608","1627":"1627"